[[File:Karl den döve.jpg|thumb|300px|SIGILLVM KAROLI FILII BENEDICTI]] '''Charles the Deaf''' ({{lang-sv|Karl Döve}}) from the [[House of Bjelbo]] was the [[jarl in Sweden|jarl]] of [[Sweden]] during 1216–1220. His father was magnate [[Bengt Snivil]]. He was the brother of [[Magnus Minnesköld]] and jarl [[Birger Brosa]] and father of jarl [[Ulf Fase]]. Charles died at the [[Battle of Lihula]] in [[Estonia]] August 8, 1220.<ref>Lindström, p 274.</ref>
The seal of Charles, discovered in the early 1990s, is dated to the end of the 12th century and thus the oldest preserved personal object in [[History of Sweden|Swedish history]]. Personal seals were normally broken to pieces at the death of the owner in order to prevent later abuse, and the intact seal of Charles is therefore unique.<ref name="auktion-sigill">Auktionsverket</ref> The [[Swedish Museum of National Antiquities]] bought it in 2001 for [[Swedish krona|SEK]] 800,000.<ref name="Rötter">Rötter</ref>
