{{NZ parlbox footer}}
Harry Bedford represented one of the multi-member [[Dunedin (New Zealand electorate)|City of Dunedin]] seats in the [[New Zealand Parliament]] from [[New Zealand general election, 1902|1902]] to 1905.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=183}}

Bedford was an [[Independent politician|Independent]] [[Liberalism|Liberal]] in 1902 topped the poll for Dunedin City with 10,088 votes. He became the sensation of the 1902 election: a political novice who had obtained the highest individual vote ever recorded in New Zealand. The Lyttelton Times described him as:  ''"the 'idol of Dunedin'...young, good-looking, able, earnest, energetic and highly attractive as a speaker".''.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper = Lyttelton Times |date =  26 November 1902|page= 6}}</ref> In {{NZ election link year|1905}}, Bedford stood for the new seat of [[Dunedin North (New Zealand electorate)|Dunedin North]] but was not successful.<ref name="Bedford"/>

He contested [[Dunedin West]] in {{NZ election link year|1911}} as an [[Independent politician|Independent]] polling 3,635 votes to 778 votes for [[James Wright Munro|Jim Munro]]. The seat was held by [[John A. Millar|John Millar]] on the second ballot. Harry Bedford joined the United Labour Party in 1912.<ref>{{citation |first = Barry |last = Gustafson |author-link = Barry Gustafson |title = The Advent of the [[New Zealand Labour Party]] 1910-1919 [M.A. - University of Auckland] |year = 1961 |page = 299}}</ref>

===Death===
Bedford drowned while swimming at [[Whangarei]] on 17 February 1918.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=SUNCH19180218.2.31 | title=Bathing fatality | date=18 February 1918 | work=The Sun | accessdate= 17 January 2016 | page=4}}</ref>

